DataElement.preferredDefinition: stage grouping, an assessment based on the combined evaluation of the patient's T stage, M stage, and N stage, assessment of a colorectal neoplasm.

DataElementConcept.preferredDefinition: information related to stage grouping, an assessment based on the combined evaluation of the patient's T stage, M stage, and N stage, assessment of a colorectal neoplasm.

ObjectClass.preferredDefinition: (ko-lo-REK-tul) Having to do with the colon or the rectum.:(NEE-o-PLAY-zha) Abnormal and uncontrolled cell growth.

Concepts.definition: Relating to the colon and rectum, or to the entire large bowel.

A benign or malignant tissue growth resulting from uncontrolled cell proliferation. Benign neoplastic cells resemble normal cells without exhibiting significant cytologic atypia, while malignant cells exhibit overt signs such as dysplastic features, atypical mitotic figures, necrosis, nuclear pleomorphism, and anaplasia. Representative examples of benign neoplasms include papillomas, cystadenomas, and lipomas; malignant neoplasms include carcinomas, sarcomas, lymphomas, and leukemias.

Concepts.definition: An assessment based on the combined evaluation of the patient's T stage, M stage, and N stage, as well as prognostic parameters for specific cancers.

ValueDomain.preferredDefinition: The stage grouping of a colorectal tumor based on the American Joint Committee on Cancer, 6th edition.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Stage Group II is subdivided into IIA and IIB on the basis of whether the primary tumor is T3 or T4, respectively.  T3: Tumor invades through the muscularis propria into the subserosa, or into non-peritonealized pericolic or perirectal tissues.  T4: Tumor directly invades other organs or structures, and/or perforates visceral peritoneum. (AJCC 6th ed.) - 2003

Concepts.longName: Stage II Colorectal Cancer AJCC v6
Concepts.definition: Stage Group II is subdivided into IIA and IIB on the basis of whether the primary tumor is T3 or T4, respectively.  T3: Tumor invades through the muscularis propria into the subserosa, or into non-peritonealized pericolic or perirectal tissues.  T4: Tumor directly invades other organs or structures, and/or perforates visceral peritoneum. (AJCC 6th ed.)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Stage 0 includes: Tis, N0, M0.  Tis: Carcinoma in situ: intraepithelial or invasion of the lamina propria.  N0: No regional lymph node metastasis.  M0: No distant metastasis. (AJCC 6th ed.)-2003

Concepts.longName: Stage 0 Colorectal Cancer AJCC v6 and v7
Concepts.definition: Stage 0 includes: Tis, N0, M0.  Tis: Carcinoma in situ: intraepithelial or invasion of the lamina propria.  N0: No regional lymph node metastasis.  M0: No distant metastasis. (AJCC 6th and 7th eds.)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Stage I includes: T1, T2 and NO, MO.  T1: Tumor invades submucosa.  T2: Tumor invades muscularis propria.  N0: No regional lymph node metastasis.  M0: No distant metastasis (AJCC 6th ed.)-2003

Concepts.longName: Stage I Colorectal Cancer AJCC v6 and v7
Concepts.definition: Stage I includes: (T1, N0, M0); (T2, N0, M0).  T1: Tumor invades submucosa.  T2: Tumor invades muscularis propria.  N0: No regional lymph node metastasis.  M0: No distant metastasis. (AJCC 6th and 7th eds.)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Stage Group III is subdivided into IIIA (T1-2, N1, M0), IIIB (T3-4, N1, M0) or IIIC (any T, N2 M0).  T1: Tumor invades the submucosa.  T2: Tumor invades muscularis propria.  T3: Tumor invades through the muscularis propria into the subserosa or into non-peritonealized pericolic or perirectal tissues.  T4: Tumor directly invades other organs or structures, and/or perforates visceral peritoneum.  N1: Metastasis in 1 to 3 regional lymph nodes N2: Metastasis in 4 or more regional lymph nodes.  M0: No distant metastasis.  (AJCC 6th ed.) - 2003

Concepts.longName: Stage III Colorectal Cancer AJCC v6
Concepts.definition: Stage Group III is subdivided into IIIA (T1-2, N1, M0), IIIB (T3-4, N1, M0) or IIIC (any T, N2 M0).  T1: Tumor invades the submucosa.  T2: Tumor invades muscularis propria.  T3: Tumor invades through the muscularis propria into the subserosa or into non-peritonealized pericolic or perirectal tissues.  T4: Tumor directly invades other organs or structures, and/or perforates visceral peritoneum.  N1: Metastasis in 1 to 3 regional lymph nodes N2: Metastasis in 4 or more regional lymph nodes.  M0: No distant metastasis.  (AJCC 6th ed.)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Stage IV includes: Any T, any N, M1.  M1: Distant metastasis. (AJCC 6th ed.) - 2003

Concepts.longName: Stage IV Colorectal Cancer AJCC v6
Concepts.definition: Stage IV includes: Any T, any N, M1.  M1: Distant metastasis. (AJCC 6th ed.)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Stage Group IIA includes T3, N0, M0. T3: Tumor invades through the muscularis propria into the subserosa, or into non-peritonealized pericolic or perirectal tissues. N0: No regional lymph node metastasis. M0: No distant metastasis. (AJCC 6th ed.) - 2003

Stage Group IIB includes T4, N0, M0. T4: Tumor directly invades other organs or structures, and/or perforates visceral peritoneum. N0: No regional lymph node metastasis. M0: No distant metastasis. (AJCC 6th ed.) - 2003

Stage Group IIIA includes T1-2, N1, M0, T1: Tumor invades the submucosa. T2: Tumor invades muscularis propria. N1: Metastasis in 1 to 3 regional lymph nodes M0: No distant metastasis. (AJCC 6th ed.) - 2003.

Stage Group IIIB includes T3-4, N1, M0.  T3: Tumor invades through the muscularis propria into the subserosa or into non-peritonealized pericolic or perirectal tissues. T4: Tumor directly invades other organs or structures, and/or perforates visceral peritoneum. N1: Metastasis in 1 to 3 regional lymph nodes. M0: No distant metastasis.(AJCC 6th ed.) - 2003

Stage Group IIIC includes Any T, N2 M0.  Any T: Tumor invades the submucosa, muscularis propria, subserosa or into non-peritonealized pericolic or perirectal tissues, or directly invades other organs or structures, and/or perforates visceral peritoneum. N2: Metastasis in 4 or more regional lymph nodes. M0: No distant metastasis. (AJCC 6th ed.) - 2003.

Concepts.definition: The extent of a cancer in the body.
